<A NAME="b">
<H3>LESSON PLANS</H3>

Middle School-High School level (Grades 7Ð12, Reading Levels 5th-12th.)<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><DL><TABLE BORDER=0><TR><TD>A.<TD>TEXTS <I>Selected Poems</I> by Langston Hughes

</TABLE></DL></BLOCKQUOTE>"Songs of Innocence" by William Blake<P>

<H4>Part One</H4>

A critical look atpoetry-rhyme patterns; free verse; subject matter; rhythm in Hughes, in Blake; picturesque language in Hughes, in Blake; sentence patterns; contractions and dialect; illustrations.<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><DL><TABLE BORDER=0><TR><TD>B.<TD>TEXTS <I>Something in Common and Other Stories</I> by Langston Hughes

</TABLE></DL></BLOCKQUOTE>"Amy Foster" by Joseph Conrad<P>

<H4>Part Two</H4>

A critical look at short stories—setting; minor characterization; thematic grouping; climax; symbolism; universality; add-a-chapter; retelling using different settings.<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><DL><TABLE BORDER=0><TR><TD>C.<TD>TEXTS <I>Not Without Laughter</I> by Langston Hughes.

</TABLE><DT><I>Stranger in a Strange Land</I> by Robert Heinlein

</DL></BLOCKQUOTE><H4>Part Three</H4>

A critical look at the novel—setting; development of major characters; plot developemnt; climax; protagonist and antagonist; recurring themea; symbolism; use of slang, dialect, other words; social significance; recommendations.<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE><DL><TABLE BORDER=0><TR><TD>D.<TD>TEXTS <I>The Big Sea</I> by Langston Hughes

</TABLE></DL></BLOCKQUOTE><H4>Part Four</H4>

Biographical study of Langston Hughes—Early life, youth, parental influence, mother image; early travels, inclination to write; first poems, love life; favorite subjects.<P>

 

